ss="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection" style="font-family: sans-serif; user-select: none; font-size: small; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; unicode-bidi: isolate;"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-right: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Python_(programming_language)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-left: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">]</span></span></h2><div class="thumb tright" style="margin: 0.5em 0px 1.3em 1.4em; width: auto; background-color: transparent; clear: right; float: right;"><div class="thumbinner" style="min-width: 100px; border: 1px solid rgb(200, 204, 209); padding: 3px; background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); font-size: 13.16px; text-align: center; overflow: hidden; width: 152px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Guido_van_Rossum_OSCON_2006_cropped.png" class="image" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/94/Guido_van_Rossum_OSCON_2006_cropped.png/150px-Guido_van_Rossum_OSCON_2006_cropped.png" decoding="async" width="150" height="225" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/94/Guido_van_Rossum_OSCON_2006_cropped.png/225px-Guido_van_Rossum_OSCON_2006_cropped.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/94/Guido_van_Rossum_OSCON_2006_cropped.png/300px-Guido_van_Rossum_OSCON_2006_cropped.png 2x" data-file-width="1175" data-file-height="1762" style="border-width: 1px; border-style: solid; border-color: rgb(200, 204, 209); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"></a><div class="thumbcaption" style="border: 0px; line-height: 1.4em; padding: 3px; font-size: 12.3704px; text-align: left;"><div class="magnify" style="float: right; margin-left: 3px; margin-right: 0px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Guido_van_Rossum_OSCON_2006_cropped.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge" style="color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: linear-gradient(transparent, transparent), url(&quot;/w/resources/src/mediawiki.skinning/images/magnify-clip-ltr.svg?8330e&quot;); background-repeat: repeat, repeat; display: block; text-indent: 15px; white-space: nowrap; overflow: hidden; width: 15px; height: 11px; user-select: none;"></a></div><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guido_van_Rossum" title="Guido van Rossum" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Guido van Rossum</a>&nbsp;at OSCON 2006</div></div></div><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" style="font-style: italic; padding-left: 1.6em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Main article:&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Python" title="History of Python" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">History of Python</a></div><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python was conceived in the late 1980s<sup id="cite_ref-venners-interview-pt-1_35-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-venners-interview-pt-1-35" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[35]</a></sup>&nbsp;by&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guido_van_Rossum" title="Guido van Rossum" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Guido van Rossum</a>&nbsp;at&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centrum_Wiskunde_%26_Informatica" title="Centrum Wiskunde &amp; Informatica" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Centrum Wiskunde &amp; Informatica</a>&nbsp;(CWI) in the&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Netherlands" title="Netherlands" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Netherlands</a>&nbsp;as a successor to the&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ABC_(programming_language)" title="ABC (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">ABC language</a>&nbsp;(itself inspired by&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SETL" title="SETL" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">SETL</a>),<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-12_36-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-12-36" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[36]</a></sup>&nbsp;capable of&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exception_handling" title="Exception handling" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">exception handling</a>&nbsp;and interfacing with the&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amoeba_(operating_system)" title="Amoeba (operating system)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Amoeba</a>&nbsp;operating system.<sup id="cite_ref-faq-created_8-1" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-faq-created-8" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[8]</a></sup>&nbsp;Its implementation began in December 1989.<sup id="cite_ref-timeline-of-python_37-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-timeline-of-python-37" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[37]</a></sup>&nbsp;Van Rossum shouldered sole responsibility for the project, as the lead developer, until 12 July 2018, when he announced his "permanent vacation" from his responsibilities as Python's&nbsp;<i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benevolent_Dictator_For_Life" class="mw-redirect" title="Benevolent Dictator For Life" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Benevolent Dictator For Life</a></i>, a title the Python community bestowed upon him to reflect his long-term commitment as the project's chief decision-maker.<sup id="cite_ref-lj-bdfl-resignation_38-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-lj-bdfl-resignation-38" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[38]</a></sup>&nbsp;He now shares his leadership as a member of a five-person steering council.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-39" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[39]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-40" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[40]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-41" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[41]</a></sup>&nbsp;In January 2019, active Python core developers elected Brett Cannon, Nick Coghlan, Barry Warsaw, Carol Willing and Van Rossum to a five-member "Steering Council" to lead the project.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-42" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[42]</a></sup></p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000 with many major new features, including a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cycle_detection" title="Cycle detection" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">cycle-detecting</a>&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garbage_collection_(computer_science)" title="Garbage collection (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">garbage collector</a>&nbsp;and support for&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unicode" title="Unicode" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Unicode</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-newin-2.0_43-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-newin-2.0-43" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[43]</a></sup></p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008. It was a major revision of the language that is not completely&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backward_compatibility" title="Backward compatibility" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">backward-compatible</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-3.0-release_44-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-3.0-release-44" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[44]</a></sup>&nbsp;Many of its major features were&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backporting" title="Backporting" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">backported</a>&nbsp;to Python 2.6.x<sup id="cite_ref-pep-3000_45-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-pep-3000-45" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[45]</a></sup>&nbsp;and 2.7.x version series. Releases of Python 3 include the&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">2to3</code>&nbsp;utility, which automates (at least partially) the translation of Python 2 code to Python 3.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-46" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[46]</a></sup></p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python 2.7's&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/End-of-life_(product)" title="End-of-life (product)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">end-of-life</a>&nbsp;date was initially set at 2015 then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-47" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[47]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-48" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[48]</a></sup></p><h2 style="font-family: &quot;Linux Libertine&quot;, Georgia, Times, serif; line-height: 1.3; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 1em 0px 0.25em; font-size: 1.5em; background: none; overflow: hidden; padding: 0px; border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177);"><span class="mw-headline" id="Features_and_philosophy">Features and philosophy</span><span class="mw-editsection" style="font-family: sans-serif; user-select: none; font-size: small; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; unicode-bidi: isolate;"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-right: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Python_(programming_language)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Features and philosophy" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-left: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">]</span></span></h2><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python is a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-paradigm_programming_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Multi-paradigm programming language" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">multi-paradigm programming language</a>.&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Object-oriented_programming" title="Object-oriented programming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Object-oriented programming</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Structured_programming" title="Structured programming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">structured programming</a>&nbsp;are fully supported, and many of its features support&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_programming" title="Functional programming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">functional programming</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aspect-oriented_programming" title="Aspect-oriented programming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">aspect-oriented programming</a>&nbsp;(including by&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metaprogramming" title="Metaprogramming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">metaprogramming</a><sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-13_49-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-13-49" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[49]</a></sup>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metaobject" title="Metaobject" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">metaobjects</a>&nbsp;(magic methods)).<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-14_50-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-14-50" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[50]</a></sup>&nbsp;Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design_by_contract" title="Design by contract" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">design by contract</a><sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-15_51-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-15-51" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[51]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-16_52-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-16-52" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[52]</a></sup>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic_programming" title="Logic programming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">logic programming</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-17_53-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-17-53" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[53]</a></sup></p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python uses&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamic_typing" class="mw-redirect" title="Dynamic typing" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">dynamic typing</a>&nbsp;and a combination of&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reference_counting" title="Reference counting" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">reference counting</a>&nbsp;and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memory_management" title="Memory management" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">memory management</a>. It also features dynamic&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Name_resolution_(programming_languages)" title="Name resolution (programming languages)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">name resolution</a>&nbsp;(<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Late_binding" title="Late binding" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">late binding</a>), which binds method and variable names during program execution.</p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python's design offers some support for&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_programming" title="Functional programming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">functional programming</a>&nbsp;in the&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lisp_(programming_language)" title="Lisp (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Lisp</a>&nbsp;tradition. It has&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">filter</code>,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">map</code>, and&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">reduce</code>&nbsp;functions;&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_comprehension" title="List comprehension" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">list comprehensions</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associative_array" title="Associative array" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">dictionaries</a>, sets, and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generator_(computer_programming)" title="Generator (computer programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">generator</a>&nbsp;expressions.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-59_54-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-59-54" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[54]</a></sup>&nbsp;The standard library has two modules (itertools and functools) that implement functional tools borrowed from&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haskell_(programming_language)" title="Haskell (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Haskell</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_ML" title="Standard ML" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Standard ML</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-18_55-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-18-55" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[55]</a></sup></p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">The language's core philosophy is summarized in the document&nbsp;<i>The&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zen_of_Python" title="Zen of Python" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Zen of Python</a></i>&nbsp;(<i>PEP 20</i>), which includes&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aphorism" title="Aphorism" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">aphorisms</a>&nbsp;such as:<sup id="cite_ref-PEP20_56-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-PEP20-56" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[56]</a></sup></p><ul style="margin: 0.3em 0px 0px 1.6em; list-style-image: url(&quot;/w/skins/Vector/resources/skins.vector.styles/images/bullet-icon.svg?d4515&quot;); padding: 0px;"><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Beautiful is better than ugly.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Explicit is better than implicit.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Simple is better than complex.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Complex is better than complicated.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Readability counts.</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Rather than having all of its functionality built into its core, Python was designed to be highly&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extensibility" title="Extensibility" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">extensible</a>. This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications. Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ABC_(programming_language)" title="ABC (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">ABC</a>, which espoused the opposite approach.<sup id="cite_ref-venners-interview-pt-1_35-1" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-venners-interview-pt-1-35" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[35]</a></sup></p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python strives for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology. In contrast to&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perl" title="Perl" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Perl</a>'s "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/There_is_more_than_one_way_to_do_it" class="mw-redirect" title="There is more than one way to do it" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">there is more than one way to do it</a>" motto, Python embraces a "there should be one‚Äîand preferably only one‚Äîobvious way to do it" design philosophy.<sup id="cite_ref-PEP20_56-1" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-PEP20-56" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[56]</a></sup>&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alex_Martelli" title="Alex Martelli" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Alex Martelli</a>, a Fellow at the Python Software Foundation and Python book author, writes that "To describe something as 'clever' is&nbsp;<i>not</i>&nbsp;considered a compliment in the Python culture."<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-19_57-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-19-57" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[57]</a></sup></p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python's developers strive to avoid&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Premature_optimization" class="mw-redirect" title="Premature optimization" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">premature optimization</a>, and reject patches to non-critical parts of the&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CPython" title="CPython" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">CPython</a>&nbsp;reference implementation that would offer marginal increases in speed at the cost of clarity.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-20_58-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-20-58" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[58]</a></sup>&nbsp;When speed is important, a Python programmer can move time-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or use&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PyPy" title="PyPy" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">PyPy</a>, a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Just-in-time_compilation" title="Just-in-time compilation" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">just-in-time compiler</a>.&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cython" title="Cython" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Cython</a>&nbsp;is also available, which translates a Python script into C and makes direct C-level API calls into the Python interpreter.</p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">An important goal of Python's developers is keeping it fun to use. This is reflected in the language's name‚Äîa tribute to the British comedy group&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monty_Python" title="Monty Python" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Monty Python</a><sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-24_59-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-24-59" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[59]</a></sup>‚Äîand in occasionally playful approaches to tutorials and reference materials, such as examples that refer to spam and eggs (from a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spam_(Monty_Python)" title="Spam (Monty Python)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">famous Monty Python sketch</a>) instead of the standard&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foobar" title="Foobar" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">foo and bar</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-60" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[60]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-61" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[61]</a></sup></p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">A common&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neologism" title="Neologism" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">neologism</a>&nbsp;in the Python community is&nbsp;<i>pythonic</i>, which can have a wide range of meanings related to program style. To say that code is pythonic is to say that it uses Python idioms well, that it is natural or shows fluency in the language, that it conforms with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability. In contrast, code that is difficult to understand or reads like a rough transcription from another programming language is called&nbsp;<i>unpythonic</i>.</p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Users and admirers of Python, especially those considered knowledgeable or experienced, are often referred to as&nbsp;<i>Pythonistas</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-27_62-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-27-62" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[62]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-25_63-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-25-63" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[63]</a></sup></p><h2 style="font-family: &quot;Linux Libertine&quot;, Georgia, Times, serif; line-height: 1.3; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 1em 0px 0.25em; font-size: 1.5em; background: none; overflow: hidden; padding: 0px; border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177);"><span class="mw-headline" id="Syntax_and_semantics">Syntax and semantics</span><span class="mw-editsection" style="font-family: sans-serif; user-select: none; font-size: small; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; unicode-bidi: isolate;"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-right: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Python_(programming_language)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Syntax and semantics" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-left: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">]</span></span></h2><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" style="font-style: italic; padding-left: 1.6em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Main article:&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_syntax_and_semantics" title="Python syntax and semantics" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Python syntax and semantics</a></div><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python is meant to be an easily readable language. Its formatting is visually uncluttered, and it often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation. Unlike many other languages, it does not use&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curly_bracket_programming_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Curly bracket programming language" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">curly brackets</a>&nbsp;to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are optional. It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_(programming_language)" title="C (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">C</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pascal_(programming_language)" title="Pascal (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Pascal</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-52_64-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-52-64" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[64]</a></sup></p><h3 style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.6; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 0.3em 0px 0px; font-size: 1.2em; background: none; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0px; border-bottom: 0px;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Indentation">Indentation</span><span class="mw-editsection" style="user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; unicode-bidi: isolate;"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-right: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Python_(programming_language)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Indentation" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-left: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">]</span></span></h3><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" style="font-style: italic; padding-left: 1.6em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Main article:&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_syntax_and_semantics#Indentation" title="Python syntax and semantics" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Python syntax and semantics ¬ß&nbsp;Indentation</a></div><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python uses&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitespace_character" title="Whitespace character" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">whitespace</a>&nbsp;indentation, rather than&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curly_bracket_programming_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Curly bracket programming language" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">curly brackets</a>&nbsp;or keywords, to delimit&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_(programming)" title="Block (programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">blocks</a>. An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-53_65-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-53-65" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[65]</a></sup>&nbsp;Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents the program's semantic structure.<sup id="cite_ref-guttag_1-1" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-guttag-1" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[1]</a></sup>&nbsp;This feature is sometimes termed the&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Off-side_rule" title="Off-side rule" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">off-side rule</a>, which some other languages share, but in most languages indentation doesn't have any semantic meaning.</p><h3 style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.6; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 0.3em 0px 0px; font-size: 1.2em; background: none; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0px; border-bottom: 0px;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Statements_and_control_flow">Statements and control flow</span><span class="mw-editsection" style="user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; unicode-bidi: isolate;"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-right: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Python_(programming_language)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Statements and control flow" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-left: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">]</span></span></h3><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python's&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statement_(computer_science)" title="Statement (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">statements</a>&nbsp;include (among others):</p><ul style="margin: 0.3em 0px 0px 1.6em; list-style-image: url(&quot;/w/skins/Vector/resources/skins.vector.styles/images/bullet-icon.svg?d4515&quot;); padding: 0px;"><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The assignment statement (token '=', the equals sign). This operates differently than in traditional&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperative_programming" title="Imperative programming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">imperative programming</a>&nbsp;languages, and this fundamental mechanism (including the nature of Python's version of&nbsp;<i>variables</i>) illuminates many other features of the language. Assignment in&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_(programming_language)" title="C (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">C</a>, e.g.,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">x = 2</code>, translates to "typed variable name&nbsp;<var style="padding-right: 1px;">x</var>&nbsp;receives a copy of numeric value 2". The (right-hand) value is copied into an&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memory_allocation" class="mw-redirect" title="Memory allocation" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">allocated storage location</a>&nbsp;for which the (left-hand)&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_(computer_science)" title="Variable (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">variable name</a>&nbsp;is the symbolic address. The memory allocated to the variable is large enough (potentially quite large) for the declared&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_system" title="Type system" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">type</a>. In the simplest case of Python assignment, using the same example,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">x = 2</code>, translates to "(generic) name x receives a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pointer_(computer_programming)" title="Pointer (computer programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">reference</a>&nbsp;to a separate, dynamically allocated&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Object_(computer_science)" title="Object (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">object</a>&nbsp;of numeric (int) type of value 2." This is termed&nbsp;<i>binding</i>&nbsp;the name to the object. Since the name's storage location doesn't&nbsp;<i>contain</i>&nbsp;the indicated value, it is improper to call it a&nbsp;<i>variable</i>. Names may be subsequently rebound at any time to objects of greatly varying types, including strings, procedures, complex objects with data and methods, etc. Successive assignments of a common value to multiple names, e.g.,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">x = 2</code>;&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">y = 2</code>;&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">z = 2</code>&nbsp;result in allocating storage to (at most) three names and one numeric object, to which all three names are bound. Since a name is a generic reference holder it is unreasonable to associate a fixed&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_system" title="Type system" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">data type</a>&nbsp;with it. However at a given time a name will be bound to&nbsp;<i>some</i>&nbsp;object, which&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;">will</span>&nbsp;have a type; thus there is&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamic_type" class="mw-redirect" title="Dynamic type" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">dynamic typing</a>.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/If-then-else" class="mw-redirect" title="If-then-else" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">if</a></code>&nbsp;statement, which conditionally executes a block of code, along with&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">else</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">elif</code>&nbsp;(a contraction of else-if).</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreach#Python" class="mw-redirect" title="Foreach" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">for</a></code>&nbsp;statement, which iterates over an iterable object, capturing each element to a local variable for use by the attached block.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/While_loop#Python" title="While loop" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">while</a></code>&nbsp;statement, which executes a block of code as long as its condition is true.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exception_handling_syntax#Python" title="Exception handling syntax" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">try</a></code>&nbsp;statement, which allows exceptions raised in its attached code block to be caught and handled by&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">except</code>&nbsp;clauses; it also ensures that clean-up code in a&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">finally</code>&nbsp;block will always be run regardless of how the block exits.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">raise</code>&nbsp;statement, used to raise a specified exception or re-raise a caught exception.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">class</code>&nbsp;statement, which executes a block of code and attaches its local namespace to a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Class_(computer_science)" class="mw-redirect" title="Class (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">class</a>, for use in&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Object-oriented_programming" title="Object-oriented programming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">object-oriented programming</a>.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">def</code>&nbsp;statement, which defines a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(computing)" class="mw-redirect" title="Function (computing)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">function</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_(computing)" class="mw-redirect" title="Method (computing)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">method</a>.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">with</code>&nbsp;statement, from Python 2.5 released in September 2006,<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-66" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[66]</a></sup>&nbsp;which encloses a code block within a context manager (for example, acquiring a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lock_(computer_science)" title="Lock (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">lock</a>&nbsp;before the block of code is run and releasing the lock afterwards, or opening a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_file" title="Computer file" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">file</a>&nbsp;and then closing it), allowing&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resource_acquisition_is_initialization" title="Resource acquisition is initialization" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Resource Acquisition Is Initialization</a>&nbsp;(RAII)-like behavior and replaces a common try/finally idiom.<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-67" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[67]</a></sup></li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Break_statement" class="mw-redirect" title="Break statement" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);"><code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">break</code></a>&nbsp;statement, exits from the loop.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">continue</code>&nbsp;statement, skips this iteration and continues with the next item.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">pass</code>&nbsp;statement, which serves as a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NOP_(code)" title="NOP (code)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">NOP</a>. It is syntactically needed to create an empty code block.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assertion_(programming)" class="mw-redirect" title="Assertion (programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">assert</a></code>&nbsp;statement, used during debugging to check for conditions that ought to apply.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">yield</code>&nbsp;statement, which returns a value from a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generator_(computer_programming)#Python" title="Generator (computer programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">generator</a>&nbsp;function. From Python 2.5,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">yield</code>&nbsp;is also an operator. This form is used to implement&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coroutine" title="Coroutine" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">coroutines</a>.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">import</code>&nbsp;statement, which is used to import modules whose functions or variables can be used in the current program. There are three ways of using import:&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">import &lt;module name&gt; [as &lt;alias&gt;]</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">from &lt;module name&gt; import *</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">from &lt;module name&gt; import &lt;definition 1&gt; [as &lt;alias 1&gt;], &lt;definition 2&gt; [as &lt;alias 2&gt;], ...</code>.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">print</code>&nbsp;statement was changed to the&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">print()</code>&nbsp;function in Python 3.</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python does not support&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tail_call" title="Tail call" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">tail call</a>&nbsp;optimization or&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First-class_continuations" class="mw-redirect" title="First-class continuations" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">first-class continuations</a>, and, according to Guido van Rossum, it never will.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-55_68-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-55-68" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[68]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-56_69-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-56-69" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[69]</a></sup>&nbsp;However, better support for&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coroutine" title="Coroutine" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">coroutine</a>-like functionality is provided in 2.5, by extending Python's&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generator_(computer_programming)" title="Generator (computer programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">generators</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-57_70-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-57-70" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[70]</a></sup>&nbsp;Before 2.5, generators were&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lazy_evaluation" title="Lazy evaluation" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">lazy</a>&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iterator" title="Iterator" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">iterators</a>; information was passed unidirectionally out of the generator. From Python 2.5, it is possible to pass information back into a generator function, and from Python 3.3, the information can be passed through multiple stack levels.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-58_71-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-58-71" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[71]</a></sup></p><h3 style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.6; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 0.3em 0px 0px; font-size: 1.2em; background: none; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0px; border-bottom: 0px;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Expressions">Expressions</span><span class="mw-editsection" style="user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; unicode-bidi: isolate;"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-right: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Python_(programming_language)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Expressions" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-left: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">]</span></span></h3><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Some Python&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expression_(computer_science)" title="Expression (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">expressions</a>&nbsp;are similar to languages such as&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_(programming_language)" title="C (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">C</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_(programming_language)" title="Java (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Java</a>, while some are not:</p><ul style="margin: 0.3em 0px 0px 1.6em; list-style-image: url(&quot;/w/skins/Vector/resources/skins.vector.styles/images/bullet-icon.svg?d4515&quot;); padding: 0px;"><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Addition, subtraction, and multiplication are the same, but the behavior of division differs. There are two types of divisions in Python. They are floor division (or integer division)&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">//</code>&nbsp;and floating point<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">/</code>division.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-72" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[72]</a></sup>&nbsp;Python also added the&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">**</code>&nbsp;operator for exponentiation.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">From Python 3.5, the new&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">@</code>&nbsp;infix operator was introduced. It is intended to be used by libraries such as&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NumPy" title="NumPy" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">NumPy</a>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_multiplication" title="Matrix multiplication" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">matrix multiplication</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-PEP465_73-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-PEP465-73" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[73]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Python3.5Changelog_74-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-Python3.5Changelog-74" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[74]</a></sup></li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">From Python 3.8, the syntax&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">:=</code>, called the 'walrus operator' was introduced. It assigns values to variables as part of a larger expression.<sup id="cite_ref-Python3.8Changelog_75-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-Python3.8Changelog-75" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[75]</a></sup></li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">In Python,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">==</code>&nbsp;compares by value, versus Java, which compares numerics by value<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-76" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[76]</a></sup>&nbsp;and objects by reference.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-77" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[77]</a></sup>&nbsp;(Value comparisons in Java on objects can be performed with the&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">equals()</code>&nbsp;method.) Python's&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">is</code>&nbsp;operator may be used to compare object identities (comparison by reference). In Python, comparisons may be chained, for example&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">a &lt;= b &lt;= c</code>.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Python uses the words&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">and</code>,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">or</code>,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">not</code>&nbsp;for its boolean operators rather than the symbolic&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">&amp;&amp;</code>,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">||</code>,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">!</code>&nbsp;used in Java and C.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Python has a type of expression termed a&nbsp;<i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_comprehension#Python" title="List comprehension" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">list comprehension</a></i>. Python 2.4 extended list comprehensions into a more general expression termed a&nbsp;<i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generator_(computer_programming)" title="Generator (computer programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">generator</a>&nbsp;expression</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-59_54-1" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-59-54" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[54]</a></sup></li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anonymous_function" title="Anonymous function" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Anonymous functions</a>&nbsp;are implemented using&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lambda_(programming)" class="mw-redirect" title="Lambda (programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">lambda expressions</a>; however, these are limited in that the body can only be one expression.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Conditional expressions in Python are written as&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">x if c else y</code><sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-60_78-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-60-78" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[78]</a></sup>&nbsp;(different in order of operands from the&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%3F:" title="?:" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">c ? x : y</a></code>&nbsp;operator common to many other languages).</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Python makes a distinction between&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_(computer_science)" class="mw-redirect" title="List (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">lists</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuple" title="Tuple" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">tuples</a>. Lists are written as&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">[1, 2, 3]</code>, are mutable, and cannot be used as the keys of dictionaries (dictionary keys must be&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immutable" class="mw-redirect" title="Immutable" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">immutable</a>&nbsp;in Python). Tuples are written as&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">(1, 2, 3)</code>, are immutable and thus can be used as the keys of dictionaries, provided all elements of the tuple are immutable. The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">+</code>&nbsp;operator can be used to concatenate two tuples, which does not directly modify their contents, but rather produces a new tuple containing the elements of both provided tuples. Thus, given the variable&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">t</code>&nbsp;initially equal to&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">(1, 2, 3)</code>, executing&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">t = t + (4, 5)</code>&nbsp;first evaluates&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">t + (4, 5)</code>, which yields&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)</code>, which is then assigned back to&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">t</code>, thereby effectively "modifying the contents" of&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">t</code>, while conforming to the immutable nature of tuple objects. Parentheses are optional for tuples in unambiguous contexts.<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-79" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[79]</a></sup></li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Python features&nbsp;<i>sequence unpacking</i>&nbsp;wherein multiple expressions, each evaluating to anything that can be assigned to (a variable, a writable property, etc.), are associated in the identical manner to that forming tuple literals and, as a whole, are put on the left hand side of the equal sign in an assignment statement. The statement expects an&nbsp;<i>iterable</i>&nbsp;object on the right hand side of the equal sign that produces the same number of values as the provided writable expressions when iterated through, and will iterate through it, assigning each of the produced values to the corresponding expression on the left.<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-80" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[80]</a></sup></li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Python has a "string format" operator&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">%</code>. This functions analogous to&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Printf_format_string" title="Printf format string" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">printf</a></code>&nbsp;format strings in&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_(programming_language)" title="C (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">C</a>, e.g.&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">"spam=%s eggs=%d"&nbsp;% ("blah", 2)</code>&nbsp;evaluates to&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">"spam=blah eggs=2"</code>. In Python 3 and 2.6+, this was supplemented by the&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">format()</code>&nbsp;method of the&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">str</code>&nbsp;class, e.g.&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">"spam={0} eggs={1}".format("blah", 2)</code>. Python 3.6 added "f-strings":&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">blah = "blah"; eggs = 2; f'spam={blah} eggs={eggs}'</code>.<sup id="cite_ref-pep-0498_81-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-pep-0498-81" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[81]</a></sup></li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Python has various kinds of&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_literal" title="String literal" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">string literals</a>:<ul style="margin-top: 0.3em; margin-right: 0px; margin-left: 1.6em; list-style-image: url(&quot;/w/skins/Vector/resources/skins.vector.styles/images/bullet-icon.svg?d4515&quot;); padding: 0px;"><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Strings delimited by single or double quote marks. Unlike in&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_shell" title="Unix shell" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Unix shells</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perl" title="Perl" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Perl</a>&nbsp;and Perl-influenced languages, single quote marks and double quote marks function identically. Both kinds of string use the backslash (<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">\\</code>) as an&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Escape_character" title="Escape character" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">escape character</a>.&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_interpolation" title="String interpolation" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">String interpolation</a>&nbsp;became available in Python 3.6 as "formatted string literals".<sup id="cite_ref-pep-0498_81-1" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-pep-0498-81" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[81]</a></sup></li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Triple-quoted strings, which begin and end with a series of three single or double quote marks. They may span multiple lines and function like&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Here_document" title="Here document" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">here documents</a>&nbsp;in shells, Perl and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_(programming_language)" title="Ruby (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Ruby</a>.</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raw_string" class="mw-redirect" title="Raw string" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Raw string</a>&nbsp;varieties, denoted by prefixing the string literal with an&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">r</code>. Escape sequences are not interpreted; hence raw strings are useful where literal backslashes are common, such as&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_expression" title="Regular expression" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">regular expressions</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Windows" title="Microsoft Windows" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Windows</a>-style paths. Compare "<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">@</code>-quoting" in&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_Sharp_(programming_language)" title="C Sharp (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">C#</a>.</li></ul></li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">Python has&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Array_index" class="mw-redirect" title="Array index" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">array index</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Array_slicing" title="Array slicing" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">array slicing</a>&nbsp;expressions on lists, denoted as&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">a[key]</code>,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">a[start:stop]</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">a[start:stop:step]</code>. Indexes are&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-based" class="mw-redirect" title="Zero-based" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">zero-based</a>, and negative indexes are relative to the end. Slices take elements from the&nbsp;<i>start</i>&nbsp;index up to, but not including, the&nbsp;<i>stop</i>&nbsp;index. The third slice parameter, called&nbsp;<i>step</i>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<i>stride</i>, allows elements to be skipped and reversed. Slice indexes may be omitted, for example&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">a[:]</code>&nbsp;returns a copy of the entire list. Each element of a slice is a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shallow_copy" class="mw-redirect" title="Shallow copy" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">shallow copy</a>.</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_Lisp" title="Common Lisp" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Common Lisp</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scheme_(programming_language)" title="Scheme (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Scheme</a>, or&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_(programming_language)" title="Ruby (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Ruby</a>. This leads to duplicating some functionality. For example:</p><ul style="margin: 0.3em 0px 0px 1.6em; list-style-image: url(&quot;/w/skins/Vector/resources/skins.vector.styles/images/bullet-icon.svg?d4515&quot;); padding: 0px;"><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_comprehensions" class="mw-redirect" title="List comprehensions" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">List comprehensions</a>&nbsp;vs.&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">for</code>-loops</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_(programming)" class="mw-redirect" title="Conditional (programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Conditional</a>&nbsp;expressions vs.&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">if</code>&nbsp;blocks</li><li style="margin-bottom: 0.1em;">The&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">eval()</code>&nbsp;vs.&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">exec()</code>&nbsp;built-in functions (in Python 2,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">exec</code>&nbsp;is a statement); the former is for expressions, the latter is for statements.</li></ul><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Statements cannot be a part of an expression, so list and other comprehensions or&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lambda_(programming)" class="mw-redirect" title="Lambda (programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">lambda expressions</a>, all being expressions, cannot contain statements. A particular case of this is that an assignment statement such as&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">a = 1</code>&nbsp;cannot form part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement. This has the advantage of avoiding a classic C error of mistaking an assignment operator&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">=</code>&nbsp;for an equality operator&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">==</code>&nbsp;in conditions:&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">if (c = 1) { ... }</code>&nbsp;is syntactically valid (but probably unintended) C code but&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">if c = 1: ...</code>&nbsp;causes a syntax error in Python.</p><h3 style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.6; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 0.3em 0px 0px; font-size: 1.2em; background: none; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0px; border-bottom: 0px;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Methods">Methods</span><span class="mw-editsection" style="user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; unicode-bidi: isolate;"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-right: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Python_(programming_language)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Methods" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-left: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">]</span></span></h3><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_(programming)" class="mw-redirect" title="Method (programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Methods</a>&nbsp;on objects are&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(programming)" class="mw-redirect" title="Function (programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">functions</a>&nbsp;attached to the object's class; the syntax&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">instance.method(argument)</code>&nbsp;is, for normal methods and functions,&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syntactic_sugar" title="Syntactic sugar" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">syntactic sugar</a>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">Class.method(instance, argument)</code>. Python methods have an explicit&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/This_(computer_programming)" title="This (computer programming)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">self</a></code>&nbsp;parameter to access&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Instance_data" class="mw-redirect" title="Instance data" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">instance data</a>, in contrast to the implicit&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">self</code>&nbsp;(or&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">this</code>) in some other object-oriented programming languages (e.g.,&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B" title="C++" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">C++</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_(programming_language)" title="Java (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Java</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Objective-C" title="Objective-C" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Objective-C</a>, or&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_(programming_language)" title="Ruby (programming language)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Ruby</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-AutoNT-61_82-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-AutoNT-61-82" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[82]</a></sup></p><h3 style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.6; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin: 0.3em 0px 0px; font-size: 1.2em; background: none; overflow: hidden; padding-top: 0.5em; padding-bottom: 0px; border-bottom: 0px;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Typing">Typing</span><span class="mw-editsection" style="user-select: none; font-size: small; font-weight: normal; margin-left: 1em; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1em; white-space: nowrap; unicode-bidi: isolate;"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-right: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Python_(programming_language)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Typing" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket" style="margin-left: 0.25em; color: rgb(84, 89, 93);">]</span></span></h3><div class="thumb tright" style="margin: 0.5em 0px 1.3em 1.4em; width: auto; background-color: transparent; clear: right; float: right;"><div class="thumbinner" style="min-width: 100px; border: 1px solid rgb(200, 204, 209); padding: 3px; background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); font-size: 13.16px; text-align: center; overflow: hidden; width: 222px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Python_3._The_standard_type_hierarchy.png" class="image" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Python_3._The_standard_type_hierarchy.png/220px-Python_3._The_standard_type_hierarchy.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="311" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Python_3._The_standard_type_hierarchy.png/330px-Python_3._The_standard_type_hierarchy.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Python_3._The_standard_type_hierarchy.png/440px-Python_3._The_standard_type_hierarchy.png 2x" data-file-width="794" data-file-height="1123" style="border-width: 1px; border-style: solid; border-color: rgb(200, 204, 209); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"></a><div class="thumbcaption" style="border: 0px; line-height: 1.4em; padding: 3px; font-size: 12.3704px; text-align: left;"><div class="magnify" style="float: right; margin-left: 3px; margin-right: 0px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Python_3._The_standard_type_hierarchy.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge" style="color: rgb(11, 0, 128); background-image: linear-gradient(transparent, transparent), url(&quot;/w/resources/src/mediawiki.skinning/images/magnify-clip-ltr.svg?8330e&quot;); background-repeat: repeat, repeat; display: block; text-indent: 15px; white-space: nowrap; overflow: hidden; width: 15px; height: 11px; user-select: none;"></a></div>The standard type hierarchy in Python 3</div></div></div><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python uses&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duck_typing" title="Duck typing" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">duck typing</a>&nbsp;and has typed objects but untyped variable names. Type constraints are not checked at&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compile_time" title="Compile time" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">compile time</a>; rather, operations on an object may fail, signifying that the given object is not of a suitable type. Despite being&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_system#Dynamic_type_checking_and_runtime_type_information" title="Type system" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">dynamically typed</a>, Python is&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strongly_typed_programming_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Strongly typed programming language" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">strongly typed</a>, forbidding operations that are not well-defined (for example, adding a number to a string) rather than silently attempting to make sense of them.</p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Python allows programmers to define their own types using&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Class_(computer_science)" class="mw-redirect" title="Class (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">classes</a>, which are most often used for&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Object-oriented_programming" title="Object-oriented programming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">object-oriented programming</a>. New&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Object_(computer_science)" title="Object (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">instances</a>&nbsp;of classes are constructed by calling the class (for example,&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">SpamClass()</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">EggsClass()</code>), and the classes are instances of the&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metaclass" title="Metaclass" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">metaclass</a>&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">type</code>&nbsp;(itself an instance of itself), allowing&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metaprogramming" title="Metaprogramming" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">metaprogramming</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflection_(computer_science)" class="mw-redirect" title="Reflection (computer science)" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">reflection</a>.</p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes:&nbsp;<i>old-style</i>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<i>new-style</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-classy_83-0" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-classy-83" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[83]</a></sup>&nbsp;The syntax of both styles is the same, the difference being whether the class&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">object</code>&nbsp;is inherited from, directly or indirectly (all new-style classes inherit from&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">object</code>&nbsp;and are instances of&nbsp;<code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">type</code>). In versions of Python 2 from Python 2.2 onwards, both kinds of classes can be used. Old-style classes were eliminated in Python 3.0.</p><p style="margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em;">The long term plan is to support&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gradual_typing" title="Gradual typing" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">gradual typing</a><sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-84" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[84]</a></sup>&nbsp;and from Python 3.5, the syntax of the language allows specifying static types but they are not checked in the default implementation, CPython. An experimental optional static type checker named&nbsp;<i>mypy</i>&nbsp;supports compile-time type checking.<sup id="cite_ref-85" class="reference" style="font-size: 11.2px; line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)#cite_note-85" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">[85]</a></sup></p><table class="wikitable" style="background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); margin: 1em 0px; border: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177);"><caption style="font-weight: bold;">Summary of Python 3's built-in types</caption><tbody><tr><th style="padding: 0.2em 0.4em; text-align: center; border: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177); background-color: rgb(234, 236, 240);">Type</th><th style="padding: 0.2em 0.4em; text-align: center; border: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177); background-color: rgb(234, 236, 240);"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immutable_object" title="Immutable object" style="background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(11, 0, 128);">Mutability</a></th><th style="padding: 0.2em 0.4em; text-align: center; border: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177); background-color: rgb(234, 236, 240);">Description</th><th style="padding: 0.2em 0.4em; text-align: center; border: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177); background-color: rgb(234, 236, 240); width: 23em;">Syntax examples</th></tr><tr><td style="padding: 0.2em 0.4em; border: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177);"><code style="font-family: monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.6px; padding-top: 1px; padding-bottom: 1px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-radius: 2px; border: 1px solid rgb(234, 236, 240);">bool</code></td><td style="padding: 0.2em 0.4em; border: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177);">immutable</td><td style="padding: 0.2em 0.4em; border: 1px solid rgb(162, 169, 177);"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_value" class="mw-redirect" title="Boolean value" style="background-image: none; bac